&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Speaker:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.pillsburylaw.com/en/lawyers/jeffrey-merrifield.html" target="_blank"&gt;The Honorable Jeffrey S. Merrifield&lt;/a&gt;,&amp;nbsp; Pillsbury Winthrop Shaw Pittman LLP&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;Title: &lt;/strong&gt;&amp;ldquo;Empowering Fusion &amp;ndash; Establishing Regulatory Frameworks to Enable the Prompt Deployment of Fusion Technologies&amp;rdquo;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
The&amp;nbsp;Honorable&amp;nbsp;Jeffrey&amp;nbsp;S.&amp;nbsp;Merrifield, who was appointed by Presidents Bill Clinton and G.W. Bush to be a Commissioner of the U.S. Nuclear Regulatory Commission (1998-2007), will discuss ongoing domestic and international efforts to establish an appropriate regulatory framework to enable the prompt deployment of fusion technologies. Currently the co-lead of Pillsbury Law Firm&amp;rsquo;s&amp;nbsp;fusion team and serving as the outside regulatory counsel of the Fusion Industry Association, Mr.&amp;nbsp;Merrifield&amp;nbsp;will discuss the process of how he assisted FIA in engaging with the NRC to set the path for an effective method to regulate this emerging technology &amp;ndash; an effort that resulted in&amp;nbsp;Merrifield&amp;nbsp;and his team being award the Financial Times 2023 Award for &amp;ldquo;Most Innovative Law Firm in the Energy Transition.&amp;rdquo;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
This talk will be offered in a hybrid format. If you wish to participate remotely, please send an email to &lt;a href="mailto:cr2090@columbia.edu?subject=Zoom%20Link%20Needed%20for%20Plasma%20Physics%20Colloquium" target="_blank"&gt;cr2090@columbia.edu&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h2&gt;2024-25 CPE Political Economy of Liquidity Seminar Series&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Session 2:&amp;nbsp;Central Banks -&amp;nbsp;Governors of or Governed by Finance?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;Monday, October 28,&amp;nbsp;2024&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Commenting on crisis management during the long Great Financial Crisis, Perry Mehrling&lt;br /&gt;
quibbed: &amp;ldquo;Forget the G7, watch the C5&amp;rdquo;. Picking up on this theme, this seminar explores the role&lt;br /&gt;
of central banks in governing finance not only in the midst of financial crises, but also&lt;br /&gt;
continuously as guardians of financial stability. Remarkably, the shadow banking system, which&lt;br /&gt;
had largely been viewed as causal for the 2008 crisis, expanded rather than contracting under the&lt;br /&gt;
watch of central banks. When faced with new episodes of financial instability, central banks have&lt;br /&gt;
responded with more large-scale asset purchases and similar measures to support the financial&lt;br /&gt;
system. This raises the question whether central banks are governing finance, or whether,&lt;br /&gt;
instead, finance is forcing central banks to dance to their tune. This is not a new question, and&lt;br /&gt;
neither is it limited to the US, or even the circle of the C5 (Fed, Bank of England, ECB, Swiss&lt;br /&gt;
CB, Bank of Japan). By putting the recent episodes of the entanglement of central banks with&lt;br /&gt;
finance into historical perspective, we are hoping to shed new light on the forces that shape&lt;br /&gt;
money, banking, and finance more broadly.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Speakers&lt;/strong&gt;:&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Lev Menand&lt;br /&gt;
Columbia Law School&lt;br /&gt;
Columbia University&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Stefano Ugolini&lt;br /&gt;
University of Toulouse&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;a href="https://forms.gle/FVAmbDuqbGfFkZzM6" target="_blank"&gt;Link to Register&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;A 60-minute session for Columbia Faculty.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Inclusive practices can empower students to engage in deeper, more meaningful learning experiences, but creating an equitable learning environment can be a challenge in the clinical setting. This session will outline the importance of inclusive teaching in the clinical setting and examine how the 5 principles of inclusive teaching outlined in the CTL&amp;rsquo;s &lt;a href="https://ctl.columbia.edu/resources-and-technology/resources/inclusive-teaching-guide/" target="_blank"&gt;&lt;em&gt;Guide for Inclusive Teaching&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt; can&amp;nbsp;be applied to the clinical education environment.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;After attending this workshop, participants should be able to:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Articulate the 5 principles outlined in the CTL&amp;rsquo;s &lt;em&gt;Guide for Inclusive Teaching&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Identify strategies for applying the first 4 principles of inclusive teaching to the clinical environment&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;You must register by 5pm on October 25, 2024 to attend this event.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Please join the Njego&amp;scaron; Endowment for Serbian Language and Culture and the Harriman Institute for a lecture by&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;Sezgin Boynik&lt;/strong&gt;. Moderated by&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;Aleksandar Bo&amp;scaron;ković&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In his lecture, Sezgin Boynik will introduce the publication Sickle of Syntax &amp;amp; Hammer of Tautology: Concrete and Visual Poetry in Yugoslavia, 1968&amp;ndash;1983, which he edited as a special number (# 90&amp;ndash;91) of OEI in 2021. Boynik will discuss example Yugoslav experimental poetry through specific historical and political context of socialist Yugoslavia.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Sickle of Syntax &amp;amp; Hammer of Tautology offers the first English-language overview of the history of the production of concrete and visual poetry in socialist Yugoslavia between 1968 and 1983. By focusing on mass-produced examples of concrete poetry, the publication presents these poetic experiments as organically linked to social movements, critical theories, and youth cultural revolutions. In his presentation, Boynik, will discuss the concrete and visual poetry in socialist Yugoslavia as an uneven and combined development, and emphasize its confrontational and organizational aspects.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Among others the publication includes accounts on the early years of OHO formation and its complex theories of words and things; an interview with Rastko Močnik on programmed art and political formalism; militant polemics of Goran Babić; Signalist contradictions; subjective structural devices of Judita &amp;Scaron;algo; zaum experiments of Vojislav Despotov; detective meta-texts of Slavoj Žižek; poetic self-management studies of Vujica Re&amp;scaron;in Tucić; a feminist historicization of Ažin school for experimental poetry; democratization of visual poetry by Westeast; selections from special issues of the journals Pitanja, Problemi, Ulaznica, Dometi, Delo, Koraci, Vidik, Pegaz, and many other materials translated into English for the first time and presented in one publication.&lt;/p&gt;

